commit_message:
Introduce hpOneView and ilorest to OneView

It introduces the hpOneView and ilorest library to the OneView
Driver. This patch will be used as the standard patch to other
patches related to the removal of the python-oneviewclient
library dependency.

Partial-Bug: #1693788
Change-Id: I77a220e8dc7099850aa5edb7a51e19ae486675a9

subject: Migrate oneview driver to use python-hpOneView

commit_message:
Migrate oneview driver to use python-hpOneView

Migrate the code on OneView drivers to stop using python-oneviewclient in
order to use python-hpOneView and python-ilorest-library. The library
python-hpOneView is more recent and is being more actively developed and
maintained.

Co-Authored-By: Rodrigo Farias <rodrigofm@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Hugo Nicodemos <nicodemos@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I731964749cb79da7178882dfc09b3fe54d8e73b4
Partial-Bug: #1693788

commit_message:
Fix persistent information when getting boot device

This patches fixes the get_boot_device methods for oneview drivers
to consider onetime boot option on the machine's iLO. If onetime
boot is set to 'Once' on iLO, the method will return persistent as
False (not persistent), True otherwise (persistent).

Change-Id: Iae837a304003cb6c17d5c40d039469b418c97421
Closes-Bug: #1706725

commit_message:
Add a timeout for powering on/off a node on HPE OneView Driver

There is an aditional timeout parameter when powering on/off
an Ironic node that is not being used at OneView drivers.

Closes-Bug: 1722616
Change-Id: Ic94b8d3c24f1ded526d3c412432b64fe328879a8

commit_message:
Migrate python-oneviewclient validations to Ironic OneView drivers

As part of the process to stop the use of python-oneviewclient
in favor of python-hpOneView and python-ilorest-library, the
validations of the python-oneviewclient have to be migrated to
the Ironic OneView drivers.

Change-Id: If1eb72192ed58b7d3b8bae780924879fed947a77
Partial-Bug: #1693788

commit_message:
Remove python-oneviewclient from Ironic OneView drivers

This patch removes the python-oneviewclient library from
OneView drivers since it was migrated to python-hponeview
and python-ilorest-library.

Change-Id: I061381a941e7d7f82863b326bb7555d41395e661
Closes-Bug: #1693788

Ruby Loo
> Thanks for the patch. I am very confused; I looked at this because it is associated with the bug 1722268, which is marked High. However, it doesn't look like the python-hpOneView client is being used in master; I don't see it in the driver-requirements.

The requirement may be seen in here https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/ironic/tree/driver-requirements.txt#n13

> This can't be a bug if it isn't actually being used by anyone?

hpOneView was introduced with the patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/468129/. But I understand your point, I am putting this as part of https://bugs.launchpad.net/ironic/+bug/1693788 instead of a new bug.

> Please clarify. it seems to me that this patch should be before whatever patch that switches to your new client. Or keep the old client - it seems to work? :)

As discussed in the channel, this patches fits better the rfe https://bugs.launchpad.net/ironic/+bug/1693788. I am changing it.

> By the way, the code looks fine. If this isn't a bug, I don't think it needs a release note. Unless there is a situation where you have a client that needs to hang around for more than 24 hours?

I put a release note because I thought it was needed for every fix. I understand what you mean though. I am removing it. Thank you

> Is there any performance issue with creating a new client? I am wondering why the original code was written the way it was.

No, in fact we could create a new client for each operation we need. 

japei
> Our old client was oneview client, this patch is part of a work to migrate to hpOneView, we are going to keep only hpOneView in the near future.


Thank you, Ruby Loo and japei, I hope I made it more clear :)"}, {'account_id': 19339, 'date': '2017-10-23 13:01:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Get a new OneView client when needed

OneView has the time to expire an active session
defined through an idle time. This idle time is
24 hours by default. The previous client,
python-oneviewclient, used by the hardware type
OneView had a reauthentication mechanism that would
ensure the new session was created when the old
one expired. With the migration to python-hpOneView,
the mechanism to reauthenticate does not exist.

This solution creates a new instance of the client when
it is needed.

Change-Id: Id112e84f7d050d818e3cd9bf02cd9cfe4716ef32
Closes-Bug: 1693788

commit_message:
Update python-ilorest-library to hardware type OneView

Previously the python-ilorest-library didn't support python3,
this patch updates the library requirement to a minimum version
that supports python3.

Change-Id: I5907267a8b2f24b915f03fc0b149a885a458fe2a

commit_message:
SUSE: Reduced required distro packages

The devel_basis pattern pulls in far too many packages but we only need
gcc so use that instead.

Change-Id: I3ba9193ba0cbff40b8bb508636c110a3921f0289

commit_message:
Fix filesystem permission masks

The setuid bit is ignored on directories, so it's not necessary
to remove it. The tasks currently remove the user's ability to
use their home directory.

The patch fixes the permissions problem, ensures that the 'nobody'
user is skipped, and enables testing for the tasks in the gate.

Closes-Bug: 1731005
Closes-Bug: 1730994
Change-Id: Id7be77b2eaa707c4c27d46f97d07f34825813749

commit_message:
Properly detect RBD in use on Cinder backends

The Cinder RBD in use host_var was not being set correctly when RBD
backends are defined in extra vars files. Instead we should use a
set_fact as implemented in Pike and master, instead of the current
broken implementation in Ocata.

A similar set fact is also added to the cinder playbook. This set
fact does not exist in Pike and master since cinder's glance API
version setting is no longer a ternary 1/2 switch, the setting is
removed since Cinder uses Glance v2 by default in Pike+. We add the
set fact here since Ocata still has a ternary switch to determine
which glance API version to use.

Change-Id: I29700603fe0ad953cde6239e4cace77c29013331

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-09 09:01:57.000000000', 'message': "Provide redirection for all security context attributes

The previous attempt at this was to redirect as little as possible.
However, this has proven to be problematic twice. auth_cacert wasn't
redirected, it was used by some of the OpenStack actions and thus
blocked Mistral patch that would have Mistral start using the new
context.

This change redirects all properties in the SecurityContext which should
be safer for our internal actions and for end users actions.

Change-Id: I6057d0ce3fe4ae23468be8fb06cb85dc5f467f6b
"}, {'created': '2017-11-09 09:04:00.000000000', 'message': "Provide redirection for all security context attributes

The previous attempt at this was to redirect as little as possible.
However, this has proven to be problematic twice. auth_cacert wasn't
redirected, it was used by some of the OpenStack actions and thus
blocked Mistral [1] patch that would have Mistral start using the new
context.

This change redirects all properties in the SecurityContext which should
be safer for our internal actions and for end users actions.

commit_message:
Provide redirection for all security context attributes

The previous attempt at this was to redirect as little as possible.
However, this has proven to be problematic twice. auth_cacert wasn't
redirected, it was used by some of the OpenStack actions and thus
blocked Mistral [1] patch that would have Mistral start using the new
context.

This change redirects all properties in the SecurityContext which should
be safer for our internal actions and for end users actions.

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/506185/14

Partial-Bug: #1718353
Needed-By: Ife653558bfcda794e7f37086832f70b0ad7c28a4

commit_message:
Fix experimental E-M-C migrations

Two closely related issues were discovered in the code which prevent
the experimental E-M-C (rolling upgrade) migration feature introduced
in Ocata from working: a malformed select statement in the ocata
community images data migration (missing function parentheses)
and an incorrect revision dependency in the DB migration (should be
'ocata_expand01' instead of 'expand'. Also added a test for the case
where the Glance database is new/empty which illuminated this bug.

Closes-Bug: 1670409
Change-Id: I40ffaaa3fa2bae7a555a86d9f31422d79fb9bb19
(cherry picked from commit 0133dc40cc22e9aa89eaf3726fdf5578fc76ec60)

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-06 08:24:29.000000000', 'message': 'diskimage_builder: lib: common-functions: Fix options for devpts mount

Commit cebfcf85f9034522a6521c40e1ae9c6d559f585f ("Use -t devpts for
/dev/pts mounts") switched from using '--bind' to '-t devpts' for
mounting the /dev/pts virtual filesystem. However, mounting devpts to
another location also affects the host's /dev/pts mountpoint. Since we
are now mounting devpts without options we end up with the following one
on openSUSE

devpts on /dev/pts type devpts (rw,nosuid,noexec,relatime,mode=600,ptmxmode=000)

instead of the one we want

devpts on /dev/pts type devpts (rw,nosuid,noexec,relatime,gid=5,mode=620,ptmxmode=000)

The missing gid=5 options results to boot problems for virtual machines

So in order to fix that, we need to use the existing devpts options for
/dev/pts so we don't lose them in the new mount.

Change-Id: I17f2c2bb96b807f8dbc07185ae0147bff3230f92
'}]
commit_message:
diskimage_builder: lib: common-functions: Fix options for devpts mount

Commit cebfcf85f9034522a6521c40e1ae9c6d559f585f ("Use -t devpts for
/dev/pts mounts") switched from using '--bind' to '-t devpts' for
mounting the /dev/pts virtual filesystem. However, mounting devpts to
another location also affects the host's /dev/pts mountpoint. Since we
are now mounting devpts without options we end up with the following one
on openSUSE

devpts on /dev/pts type devpts (rw,nosuid,noexec,relatime,mode=600,ptmxmode=000)

instead of the one we want

devpts on /dev/pts type devpts (rw,nosuid,noexec,relatime,gid=5,mode=620,ptmxmode=000)

The missing gid=5 options results to boot problems for virtual machines

So in order to fix that, we need to use the existing devpts options for
/dev/pts so we don't lose them in the new mount.

Change-Id: I17f2c2bb96b807f8dbc07185ae0147bff3230f92

commit_message:
Automatically remove images that are larger than image_size_cap

When a user uploads an image that exceeds the image_size_cap configured in
glance-api.conf, they recieve an error, but the record of the image persists
in the database. This should be removed automatically

Change-Id: Ic076220e87e48183646140f31fe0b1d3e79ba789
Closes-Bug: #1726518

commit_message:
Don't calculate hashes for rh1 images

Don't calculate hashes for rh1 images because of lack of
constant mirroring with rdo cloud, let they use current-tripleo
as usual.

Change-Id: Icef7421185960e428e7771f1fefb4f9e71b88e8a

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-18 16:21:40.000000000', 'message': 'Add Apache packages to mistral-api container

Some projects that use Kolla docker containers (TripleO) run
mistral-api under httpd. This patch adds the httpd package so that it
exists in the container and can optionally by used via Docker
entrypoints.

As many of these projects do not require the use of Apache (it is
opt-in) at this point not all deployment frameworks support the use of
it so the existing configuration defaults have been left as-is for now.

commit_message:
Add Apache packages to mistral-api container

Some projects that use Kolla docker containers (TripleO) run
mistral-api under httpd. This patch adds the httpd package so that it
exists in the container and can optionally by used via Docker
entrypoints.

As many of these projects do not require the use of Apache (it is
opt-in) at this point not all deployment frameworks support the use of
it so the existing configuration defaults have been left as-is for now.

Change-Id: I07ffd0b398e20065fff27c30d0842b94090ca0ad
Related-Bug: #1724607
Partially-Implements: blueprint apache-packages-for-apis

commit_message:
Set become:false for undercloud plays

Since the undercloud is localhost, ansible skips ssh and just runs local
commands. That will cause problems when running ansible-playbook under
the mistral workflow because the mistral user can not use sudo. Set
become:false on all the undercloud plays as sudo is not actually needed.

Change-Id: I2980c584d2f4ee5c2de3720eecfc80cc43ee1fa6
implements: blueprint ansible-config-download

commit_message:
Ensure HTTPS configuration completes

There was a race where the https apache2 site,
openstack_https_frontend.conf, would be rendered in one hook, then
subsequently the config-changed hook would run and enable that site.
However, the subsequent config-changed hook would see the template as
having not changed and therefore it would fail to restart apache2.
This lead to apache2 failing to listen on the correct ports.

This was due to CONFIGS.write_all() being called but a2ensite not
being called. This change fixes this race and adds a call to
configure_https() to ensure the configuration completes and apache2
is restarted.

Change-Id: I229d25c707a0630c9d609fd20a962a0de2e42c77
Closes-Bug: #1723892

commit_message:
Import midonet config in each service driver

This allows midonet plugins to be specified in any order
and not have to worry about import orders. Currently
some drivers could be loaded without the midonet config being
registered with oslo_config.

Change-Id: I1f62228437d1c27bd35c2df1dc9364297591eaf5
Closes-Bug: #1729751

commit_message:
Fixed creation neutron api mapping for security groups

Fixed creation of security group and security group rule via
neutronclient api mapping.
There was a switch from novaclient to neutronclient
for creating a security groups and rules in change
5d5666b10e57a94bcde06c8a296002175d935c7b but
the argument mapping for this function has not been changed.

Change-Id: I1774b73c61adb3b44a61f3f56f99e85f278deb83
Closes-Bug: 1716922
(cherry picked from commit c93f5833e4100d2325994b1bdf8f0d12b70d00c7)

commit_message:
Add option for nova compute container to log to stdout/stderr

This adds the option to get the nova-compute container to log to stdout.
The option is disabled by default.

bp logging-stdout-rsyslog

Change-Id: Id09f4c439987ce3d668d53932e5a4dc6ee3b280d

commit_message:
Implement policy in code - client (end)

This commit migrate all client policies into code [1] and
also remove policy.json usage file completely.

Like oslo.config, with oslo.policy, we can define all of
default rules in code base and only change some rules
via policy file. Another thing that we should use yaml
format instead of json format.

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/queens/policy-in-code.html
Co-authored-By: Dai Dang-Van <daidv@vn.fujitsu.com>

Change-Id: I7c7fd83aa2516c053e38d7598cf79e63401f7519

commit_message:
Use latest RAW image for OVB Deployment on rdocloud

Currently we are using QCow2 image, We should use a Raw image
as it would help reducing IO(take advantage of ceph Copy on Write)
during creation of undercloud vm(boot from volume currently).
The patch updates the ovb deployment on RDO Cloud to use the latest
RAW image available, which is CentOS-7-x86_64-GenericCloud-1708.

Change-Id: I27eaac609abfffbb73821756bc90aab625daeb23

Implement policy in code - backup (5)

This commit migrate all backup policies into code [1].

Like oslo.config, with oslo.policy, we can define all of
default rules in code base and only change some rules

commit_message:
Remove warning during kolla_docker execution

Ansible check if modules parameters are named like
%password% and allow to hidden log param in this case.
This requires adding "no_log" parameters.
This patch just add "no_log" param in order to avoid
this warning.

Change-Id: I9c1df1093e0fd101090292d6e8bf3527f99aeb17
Closes-Bug: #1702244

commit_message:
Add retries to read-only db operations

To prevent possible failures because of operational errors
we should add retries and send additional requests to the
database.

This change will increase the overall stability of the system
and will avoid obscure errors from the database.

Change-Id: I9ddef565acabbbfaddcb96f6a850a21875e6dcd5
Closes-bug: #1730426
(cherry picked from commit bff3ebf30b46b0825c075531f8d997467e4b1c69)

commit_message:
Implement policy in code - job (2)

This commit migrate all job policies into code [1].

Like oslo.config, with oslo.policy, we can define all of
default rules in code base and only change some rules
via policy file. Another thing that we should use yaml
format instead of json format.

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/queens/policy-in-code.html
Co-authored-By: Dai Dang-Van <daidv@vn.fujitsu.com>

Change-Id: Ia80ee3eb4617cab66b4529e501ca72d2a38b7eba

commit_message:
Fix NoneType has no attribute get error

If volume_type is None and then create volumes with allow-multiattach,
Cinder-schduler will raise error:
AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'get'

Ied42d13b642617dd239ea92c019354b90657821a didn't fix it completely.
The error still exists. Here is the reproduce command:
"cinder create 1 ----allow-multiattach"

Because that the volume_type is always in the "request_spec", if
users doesn't pass it, its value is None.

Change-Id: I1140234dd69a644dcbf6fc3a01f382ee101624b2
Related-bug: #1683431
(cherry picked from commit f3d66c3254f7a5424be4088dfa767f128ae6cfc3)

commit_message:
Enable bridge command for openvswitch agent

Allow ovs agent to run bridge command.
This is necessary because FDB extension uses bridge to update the FDB table.

Closes-Bug: #1730407

Change-Id: I0897f1efcf36fc7f6f06e80c3b29c0e1fa14b141

commit_message:
Use dict.keys() for key iteratation

1.As mentioned in [1], we should avoid usingg
six.iteritems to achieve iterators. We can
use dict.items instead, as it will return
iterators in PY3 as well. And dict.items/keys
will more readable. 2.In py2, the performance
about list should be negligible, see the link [2].
[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3
[2] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/066391.html

Change-Id: If262e92b06e6cdef7429bd55549435c98e39c603

commit_message:
Remove check flat network type task in ironic pre-check.yml

flat network type is not mandatory. There are two cases,

1. ironic with flat network: we can use neutron vlan network to
   provision baremetal nodes, as long as the interface of the baremetal
   nodes are configured to use the same vlan.

2. ironic with neutron network: all provision and cleaning_network can
   be vlan type and no flat is needed at all.

So we should remove the task.

Change-Id: I176ded6d2a8b14e350f665f63bc37eb488d32679
Closes-Bug: #1725170
(cherry picked from commit 175c65e4900c9cc68917242fd7c9677fc32a2087)

commit_message:
Make docker network configurable

The default docker0 address conflicts with the InternalApiNetCidr value
set in environments/network-environment.yaml. We should provide a way
to make the docker network configurable.

Change-Id: Ie803b33c93b931f7fefb87b6833eb22fd59cd92d
Related-Bug: #1726773
(cherry picked from commit 4462260182b5b6a8922193aff3ff603bbb93cf00)

commit_message:
devstack: Clean up some of the devstack code

Mostly inspired by some comments left in the review of commit
aa5fd8afdc31b95c1a5f91f8af5fa733c4afd121 (Allow to set default ifaces
in DevStack)

Sorted the list of enabled interfaces and the default interface
values.

Used a local variable to store the uppercase value, in order to make
the code more readable as people may not immediately know what
${var^^} does in bash.

Change-Id: Ic2b2ac0a3cea9fa39173c5e2f5a9eaa3f4d8d2e4

commit_message:
RHSM: when using proxy, test its connectivity first

When using RHSM with a proxy, we want to make sure the proxy can be
reached. This patch verify that a tcp socket can be open from the client
to the proxy.

This patch also does a bit of refactoring:
- --retry-delay 10 --max-time 30 is now used in a parameter everytime we
  use curl.
- proxy options are now used everytime curl is used, even for detecting
  which version of Satellite is running, now we use proxy options.

Co-Authored-By: Vincent S. Cojot <vincent@cojot.name>
Change-Id: I4dcac1528c10f698338383445e27c8a613f9bcd9
Closes-Bug: #1724970
(cherry picked from commit f4e46f4b3ddac3f536a3a1955c91447e8b26ffca)

commit_message:
Fix uses of old deprecated constants in DISCO driver

os-brick removes old connector constants on v2.0 with
Ia18de03880ca5b04d31dbdf7891fa6d3240ae9b5 patch.

All drivers must use new constants to work with the latest
supported os-brick version

Closes-Bug: #1731000
Change-Id: I451feb5796a29b8003537a504e36144bcf225a4f

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-02 14:08:56.000000000', 'message': "Murano application should contact rabbitmq by external FQDN

In case of external router internal VIP and external VIP are the
same. External router manages port/address redirection from
public network to OpenStack API. The address of the router is
set via 'kolla_external_fqdn'. Currently Murano configuration
that is handed over to Murano application instance uses
'kolla_external_vip_address'. This leads to the instance trying
to connect to internal API network. Correct address should be
'kolla_external_fqdn' which will work in both cases - either with
double VIP setup or with single VIP + external router.

Change-Id: I78c38ae0af1cecd2be2b1c6cc86bcfc51b847082
Closes-Bug: #1729611
"}]
commit_message:
Murano application should contact rabbitmq by external FQDN

In case of external router internal VIP and external VIP are the
same. External router manages port/address redirection from
public network to OpenStack API. The address of the router is
set via 'kolla_external_fqdn'. Currently Murano configuration
that is handed over to Murano application instance uses
'kolla_external_vip_address'. This leads to the instance trying
to connect to internal API network. Correct address should be
'kolla_external_fqdn' which will work in both cases - either with
double VIP setup or with single VIP + external router.

Change-Id: I78c38ae0af1cecd2be2b1c6cc86bcfc51b847082
Closes-Bug: #1729611

commit_message:
Fix horizon doesn't handle static files error

the `/tmp` directory is mounted from host, so it's better to write the
temp file to other place, use $HOME in this case.

Change-Id: I459306ffbf48dbe98e22725e8edb3ace8bb558bb
Closes-Bug: #1722202

Clean up npm package dependencies

npm dependency packages are installed for js unit tests,
and not necessary in production.
Move all contents from `dependencies` to `devDependencies`
 in package.json

(2 comments)

There's a section in service.py that looks like this:

        if cancel_with_rollback:  # Commanded by user
            allowed_actions = (current_stack.UPDATE,)
        else:  # Cancelled by parent stack
            allowed_actions = (current_stack.UPDATE, current_stack.CREATE)

So with rollback we can only cancel updates, but without rollback we can also cancel creates.

The API is called update-cancel, but maybe this behaviour is what we want anyway? In any event, at the very least the comments are out of date with this change."}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2017-09-28 03:53:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

(2 comments)

> The API is called update-cancel, but maybe this behaviour is what we want anyway?

Yeah, though it can be little confusing, I did not make any changes to the rpc api to avoid complexity.

Also, I think the existing osc command is called 'stack cancel', where the user is presented with an error, if create is cancelled. 

OK, I'll cleanup the comments in service.py."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2017-10-03 22:36:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

(1 comment)

Another thing I just remembered... we should allow cancel without rollback from the command line only for convergence stacks. But we still need to allow it _internally_ for non-convergence stacks. That might require a change to the RPC protocol since they both rely on the same message, or perhaps we could get away with passing a value other than True/False that gets interpreted the right way by the previous code, so that we can avoid any RPC versioning issues.'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2017-10-04 11:25:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

> we should allow cancel without rollback from the command line only for convergence stacks

Any reason other than the fact that we cancel the thread with legacy stack(hence db issues)? It seems to work ok with my limited tests though.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2017-10-04 16:36:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

I think I had a reason at one point in time, but I don't recall it so it may have been specious ;)

In general, I'd like to avoid adding new features to the legacy path though. Just because I don't want to have to support them. It's too much to think about already."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-10-05 03:31:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add REST api support for cancel without rollback

We already have REST api support for cancelling a
UPDATE_IN_PROGRESS stack with rollback. This adds a
new action 'cancel_without_rollback' to allow for
canceling a create/update in_progress stack without
rollback.

APIImpact

Change-Id: I6c6ffa0502ab8745cfb2f9c5ef263f1e02dfc4ca
Closes-Bug: #1709041

commit_message:
Add option to ignore failures due to missing files

TripleO started using j2 template versions of environment files, and in
the normal workflow the templates are all rendered before calling the
process_multiple_environments_and_files() function. However, in certain
cases it can happen the j2 templates are not yet rendered by the time
we call the process_multiple_environments_and_files() function. In this
case it's OK to ignore the missing files.

This commit add a new `ignore_missing` boolean option to
process_multiple_environments_and_files() and related functions to
ignore missing files instead of returning an error.

Change-Id: Ia78e271ccdaf2618d4f0837ef84546f9d17b6822
Related-Bug: #1730650

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

hi Jelmer, who calls these functions in teamcity.py? Does teamcity have some sort of API or plugin arch?'}, {'account_id': 26351, 'date': '2017-07-14 12:36:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

First, my apologies for leaving this broken for so long. I completely forgot that I still had an issue to fix in this, so I'll have a look at this over the weekend.

 > hi Jelmer, who calls these functions in teamcity.py? Does teamcity
 > have some sort of API or plugin arch?

You need to configure a build step in a TeamCity build config, and call bandit with the teamcity formatter in that build step. For example, we use this in our template for all Python projects as follows:

if [ -f %teamcity.build.checkoutDir%/inspections/bandit.ini ]; then
  bandit -r . -f teamcity --ini %teamcity.build.checkoutDir%/inspections/bandit.ini -c %teamcity.build.checkoutDir%/inspections/bandit.yml 
fi

In other words, you enable bandit on your code by adding inspections/bandit.{ini,yml} with the relevant parameters in your repository. Note that the relevant part for the formatter is hardcoded in the build step (-f teamcity).

TeamCity will pick up stdout from bandit and parse it accordingly."}, {'account_id': 17893, 'date': '2017-07-14 13:22:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 17893, 'date': '2017-07-14 13:25:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

the above "recheck" will trigger jenkins checks again (so we can study the failures).

sounds like a documentation patch might be useful as well, with details on what config directives need to be used for teamcity. I trust you have tested this with a teamcity instance locally. I am just thinking how we would test this going forward, do you have any ideas on some unit tests?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-07-14 13:30:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> sounds like a documentation patch might be useful as well, with
 > details on what config directives need to be used for teamcity. I
 > trust you have tested this with a teamcity instance locally.

I may be missing something, but the formatter framework was already there for me to expand upon. If the documentation simply lists that there is "a TeamCity formatter" a capable user should be able to find out using the other pieces of the documentation and the CLI help text how to enable that formatter.

The only thing that is TeamCity-specific is the formatter. The other parts (supplying configuration through yml and ini) are only as mandatory as the core of bandit makes it, and don't touch the TeamCity-specific part.

 > I am just thinking how we would test this going forward, do you 
 > have any ideas on some unit tests?

Good point, I had not yet thought of that. I see there are already some unit tests for the other formatters, so simply taking one of those and modifying the expected output would be a good start. The only thing that might be different in this formatter that requires some additional testing is the fact that every error code is printed as an inspection type only once, and only if it is referenced from another inspection later on. It should not be too difficult to validate that part with a separate test.

Chronologically speaking, my first goal would be to get Jenkins to stop failing on the code that is already there. Once that is done I will look into the unit tests.'}, {'account_id': 17893, 'date': '2017-07-14 15:00:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Zuul: add file extension to playbook path

Zuul now supports including the file extension on the playbook path
and omitting the extension is now deprecrated.  Update references
to include the extension.

Change-Id: I26a04575de845c1f09e5853191e064f4b285222c

Jakub, if I'm reading the code right this looks like it can create sub processes to deal with both elasticsearch and the metrics DB from the same parent process.  Do you think making this depend on two DBs at the same time makes the system more fragile?  Would it be better to run two instances of the persister so that errors in one DB don't effect data being sent to the other?  If we do want to handle both DBs from one parent process is there a way to make this more robust so we can only bounce the child process on errors?"}, {'account_id': 23043, 'date': '2017-08-08 04:32:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21:

> Jakub, if I'm reading the code right this looks like it can create
 > sub processes to deal with both elasticsearch and the metrics DB
 > from the same parent process.  Do you think making this depend on
 > two DBs at the same time makes the system more fragile?  Would it
 > be better to run two instances of the persister so that errors in
 > one DB don't effect data being sent to the other?  If we do want to
 > handle both DBs from one parent process is there a way to make this
 > more robust so we can only bounce the child process on errors?

Well, this change allows to process both metrics and events, however, it would be recommended to run two instances of persister - just as you pointed out. I mean, for the development/testing/preview a single instance could be good enough. But on the other hand, for production it would be better to have both flows separated and independent."}, {'account_id': 14273, 'date': '2017-09-30 05:27:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 26141, 'date': '2017-10-03 10:12:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 26733, 'date': '2017-10-05 13:44:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 16168, 'date': '2017-10-06 07:45:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22: Patch Set 21 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-10-06 08:52:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add support for persisting events

This change extends the persister to read OpenStack
event objects from kafka topic and then stores
them into ElasticSearch.

Story: 2001112
Task: 4843

Change-Id: I35b0db67dc088e56ad281c84fc4b50fa7a064e44

commit_message:
Re-enable containerized fluentd

Now that we got a promotion, there is a container image for fluentd in
tripleomaster registry. We can finally re-enable the containerized
fluentd service in scenario0001.

Change-Id: I636e63f9b66dd47267fa40febf49a6ec9a6b7ef3
Related-Bug: #1721723
Closes-Bug: #1726891

commit_message:
Fix wrong permission on database during mysql_init tasks.

During mysql initialization, mysql needs to be able to write in the
database directory.

Change-Id: I82c2e46f66ab01021cb910eb7e0d17c81b00fa09
Closes-bug: #1730349
(cherry picked from commit 0d65e380caf89d8c486e8ea87571298a6687b680)

Set bind mount propegatation to shared for /var/lib/nova.

visible to nova_libvirt.

commit_message:
Derive params support for ODL DPDK feature

Adding ODL DPDK condition to check whether DPDK feature
is enabled or not in ODL to support the derive parameters.
DPDK feature is enabled in ODL if OvsEnableDpdk
parameter is enabled in role parameters.

Change-Id: I64392c1cb96d8d40d22e70ed7992bb267cb27822
Closes-bug: #1714461
(cherry picked from commit 1444c1d16bb289effd56d03b363c86e350f9497a)

commit_message:
Do not set cluster in maintenance mode during split stack upgrade

This change noops ControllerDeployedServer{Pre,Post}Config to avoid
getting the upgrade of a split stack deployment getting stuck due
to the cluster being in maintenance mode. For reference a similar
change has been done for the regular Controller role in:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/487313/

Change-Id: Idd393011b3c4d0d236780e11a04a59d426750de1
Closes-bug: 1725175
(cherry picked from commit 8e92d7c6db6fcae863a250f63b01a98f7a3f3340)

commit_message:
Set ipc=host for services attaching encrypted volumes

Without ipc=host set, cryptsetup/devicemapper will never
see devices created when running "cryptsetup luksOpen",
causing the command to hang.

This is required for attaching encrypted Cinder volumes.

Closes-Bug: #1729419
Change-Id: Ic7184b1fbbafea266f8ec1e7974d0a4a2cf4d750
(cherry picked from commit 05b61472463d5dbde3f1b1285819044409a80e2e)

commit_message:
Replace logging with oslo_log

The oslo.log (logging) configuration library provides standardized
configuration for all openstack projects. It also provides custom
formatters, handlers and support for context specific logging (like
resource id's etc).
I think it's better to use the common logging module.

Change-Id: I882dfafc6101ba3b74b8e0ef120bfab03f602cb6

commit_message:
Drop py34 target in tox.ini and setup.cfg

We support py35 now.We do not have python 3.4 in setup.cfg which declares the explicit
supported versions.so it is no need to keep the supoort for py34.
see:https://review.openstack.org/#/c/349069/

Change-Id: I476527b98fbb065fcfd82d707fca70b364518975

commit_message:
Fix grafana configuration to neutron-dynamic-routing periodic job

Currently grafana does not display results of periodic job for
neutron-dynamic-routing as grafana configuration to periodic job
is defined in an incorrect file for [1] and the file has incorrect
job name for [2].

[1] periodic-neutron-dynamic-routing-dsvm-tempest-with-ryu-master-scenario-ipv4
[2] periodic-neutron-dynamic-routing-py35-with-neutron-lib-master

Change-Id: Ie29713fc4e1123dce4dee3458ad9f2a0f357e07d

commit_message:
Support insecure SSL when talking to services

The certificates may not be known to Trove when doing requests
to the different services so support insecure requests. This
can be configured via the new config options

- nova_api_insecure
- cinder_api_insecure
- neutron_api_insecure
- swift_api_insecure

All new config parameters default to 'False' so nothing changes
if not explicitly configured.

This is useful if the services use SSL adn Trove wants to talk to theses
services without configuring the different certs.

Change-Id: Ib59abd1500baad132e5c9f53895fd1eca18ac4d7
Closes-Bug: #1535895

subject: Added pytest support to setup.py test
messages:
[{'account_id': 25290, 'date': '2017-02-25 12:00:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2017-02-25 12:00:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more

commit_message:
Added pytest support to setup.py test

It might be useful for small projects where 'testr' or 'nose' usage is
expensive.

Change-Id: I8048ed91287f9b11219d1ce6cf61ad1a91bb1482
Signed-off-by: Mikhail Ushanov <gm.mephisto@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Unset MountFlags in docker.service systemd directives

Required to allow bind propegation options to be set on individual bind-mounts.
See https://github.com/moby/moby/issues/19625.

Also https://access.redhat.com/articles/2938171 for rational for using this
option in RHEL/CentOS 7.3.

Change-Id: I8a63c044e15d7ca0f54654e9fc9c5d878461aa25
Related-bug: 1730533
(cherry picked from commit 2366b5b2fe3bc97d11aa9c3a65660ff78a6dc6f7)

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-01 16:00:53.000000000', 'message': "Add --detailed-exitcodes when running puppet via ansible

puppet run on never fails, even when it should, since we moved
to the ansible way of applying it. The reason is the current following code:

    - name: Run puppet host configuration for step {{step}}
      command: >-
        puppet apply
        --modulepath=/etc/puppet/modules:/opt/stack/puppet-modules:/usr/share/openstack-puppet/modules
        --logdest syslog --logdest console --color=false
        /var/lib/tripleo-config/puppet_step_config.pp

The above is missing the --detailed-exitcodes switch and so puppet will never
really error out on us and the deployment will keep on running all the
steps even though a previous puppet manifest might have failed. This
cause extra hard-to-debug failures.

Initially the issue was observed on the puppet host runs, but this
parameter is missing also from docker-puppet.py, so let's add it there
as well as it makes sense to return proper error codes whenever we call
puppet.

Besides this being a good idea in general, we actually *have* to do it
because puppet does not fail correctly without this option due to the
following puppet bug:
https://tickets.puppetlabs.com/browse/PUP-2754

Co-Authored-By: Damien Ciabrini <dciabrin@redhat.com>

Change-Id: Ie9df4f520645404560a9635fb66e3af42b966f54
Closes-Bug: #1723163
(cherry picked from commit 11e599d116cfbf7df4dcd0e7670c3405a4224c1a)

commit_message:
Add --detailed-exitcodes when running puppet via ansible

puppet run on never fails, even when it should, since we moved
to the ansible way of applying it. The reason is the current following code:

    - name: Run puppet host configuration for step {{step}}
      command: >-
        puppet apply
        --modulepath=/etc/puppet/modules:/opt/stack/puppet-modules:/usr/share/openstack-puppet/modules
        --logdest syslog --logdest console --color=false
        /var/lib/tripleo-config/puppet_step_config.pp

The above is missing the --detailed-exitcodes switch and so puppet will never
really error out on us and the deployment will keep on running all the
steps even though a previous puppet manifest might have failed. This
cause extra hard-to-debug failures.

Initially the issue was observed on the puppet host runs, but this
parameter is missing also from docker-puppet.py, so let's add it there
as well as it makes sense to return proper error codes whenever we call
puppet.

Besides this being a good idea in general, we actually *have* to do it
because puppet does not fail correctly without this option due to the
following puppet bug:
https://tickets.puppetlabs.com/browse/PUP-2754

Co-Authored-By: Damien Ciabrini <dciabrin@redhat.com>

Change-Id: Ie9df4f520645404560a9635fb66e3af42b966f54
Closes-Bug: #1723163

commit_message:
Temporarily disable fluentd from scenario001-multinode-containers

Mixing containers and BM is currently not working. Once the master
promotion will take place we will have a fluentd container and
can readd fluentd as a container and the problem should not re-occurr.

Change-Id: Iad97f7e0e4de56f46a46d2381fc1ea5822a2114a
Related-Bug: #1726891
(cherry picked from commit 35d91ddc6d11bb2696321fff4593d5cca3b0cba8)

commit_message:
Should not allow security group from other project pass API layer check when booting

Currently, the default behavior of neutron when list security groups is:
if you are "admin", response everything we have in the env, and if the
user uses a security group from other project to boot a server, Nova will
show no error in API layer check but error raised in compute layer.

This patch added a check of security group project_id with the
context project uuid, and raises exception.SecurityGroupNotAllowedToUse
if they don't match.

Change-Id: I04a9ccf75b871fd6b519d9fa79d229e6a2da1a3e
Closes-bug: #1691902

commit_message:
Should generate migration record after successfully claimed

Currently the migration record was generated before successful
claim, this may lead to an bad migration record if the claim
failed afterwards and reschedule also failed.

It could be better if we generate the migration records after
successfully claimed.

Change-Id: I63883ba3c2a27759a0d87fc3e782f9190f0acdc1
Closes-Bug: #1661793

commit_message:
Fix mysql instance create failed when enable skip-name-resolve

In the guestagent code, it create os_admin user only grant
privileges on host:localhost, but use host:127.0.0.1 to
connect to mysql. Modify host privileges grant on to 127.0.0.1
to avoid create instance failed when enable skip-name-resolve
in config file.

Change-Id: Ifa69461c8a55464f88aec001d067450eedccf172
Closes-bug: #1729225

commit_message:
Add --workflow-name for specifying a custom workflow

A new cli arg, --workflow-name, is added to the "openstack overcloud
deploy" command which allows for overriding the default workflow name
used for deploying the overcloud.

A custom workflow could be specified to use the config-download steps
added in I7d7f6b831b8566390d8f747fb6f45e879b0392ba, or optionally, just
do the Heat deploy and then allow for manual running of the
ansible-playbook commands. These workflows will be added later, and this
cli arg will allow the user to choose which to use during overcloud
deployment.

blueprint ansible-config-download

Change-Id: Ibd981e533bfd7f7369a6b9c7fdcc39629d4e5ed7

commit_message:
Add --workflow-input to pass custom input to workflow

Adds a new cli arg --workflow-input that can be used to pass custom
workflow input values to the workflow used for deployment. In
combination with the previous patch,
Ibd981e533bfd7f7369a6b9c7fdcc39629d4e5ed7, this allows one to pass any
input value to a custom workflow provided by --workflow-name.

Change-Id: I016fefa91b222bde7af9d274bc9fd428d4ef5546
implements: blueprint ansible-config-download

commit_message:
Do not use “-y” for package install

According to "code conventions" [1], do not use "-y" option.
Instead, use apt-get install package, yum install package,
or zypper install package.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/doc-contrib-guide/writing-style/
code-conventions.html

Change-Id: I174c8a0c653e322bbf951d72445b1a43251baa7e

[{'created': '2017-11-07 22:05:13.000000000', 'message': "use qos api def from neutron-lib

The Qos extension's API definition was rehomed into neutron-lib with
commit I8ab3712850ec02278b3efb9161fc03236926b842 and neutron will
consume it with I3bb987920008d5a1d73cf4c5f37895d7f917c368

This patch removes the global attribute map update for the qos
extension in the Unit Tests. This isn't needed and is already handled in
extension loading.

commit_message:
use qos api def from neutron-lib

The Qos extension's API definition was rehomed into neutron-lib with
commit I8ab3712850ec02278b3efb9161fc03236926b842 and neutron will
consume it with I3bb987920008d5a1d73cf4c5f37895d7f917c368

This patch removes the global attribute map update for the qos
extension in the Unit Tests. This isn't needed and is already handled in
extension loading.

Change-Id: I0a3bf607ef5197feac3f0fb4468027110971a10d

commit_message:
Do not use “-y” for package install

According to "code conventions" [1], do not use "-y" option.
Instead, use apt-get install package, yum install package,
or zypper install package.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/doc-contrib-guide/writing-style/
code-conventions.html

Change-Id: I58d11d0bb8976941ceda56a95112783090d211bf

commit_message:
Zuul: add file extension to playbook path

Zuul now supports including the file extension on the playbook path
and omitting the extension is now deprecrated.  Update references
to include the extension.

Change-Id: I888edf46f6f3a3ada068684162fcad382a019393
(cherry picked from commit f3dc082d40f666c888a17c166735b448e2fa4116)

makes sense, thanks!'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-10-30 13:59:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-10-30 14:00:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2: Commit message was updated.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-10-30 14:01:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm still wondering if we can really even test this easily"}, {'account_id': 10267, 'date': '2017-10-30 14:25:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

No, it won't solve the problem.

I think we have to move
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/agent/l3/agent.py#L613-L615

inside function _process_updated_router()"}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-10-30 15:15:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Oh, now I see, _router_added() does this:

  self.router_info[router_id] = ri

then calls ri.initialize(), so ri is valid in check_ha_state_for_router() when the period task is called.

So let it add the router to the queue and process it later, and ha_state() shouldn't trigger an exception then because SYNC is lower in priority than the RPC call that might have been just creating this."}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-10-31 20:25:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-10-31 20:26:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow-1

DNM yet.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-10-31 23:49:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 12860, 'date': '2017-11-01 04:04:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10267, 'date': '2017-11-03 04:55:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 10267, 'date': '2017-11-03 04:58:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-11-03 15:02:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Workflow-1

recheck

Anil, this almost doesn't seem necessary after https://review.openstack.org/#/c/517097/ - we'll have to chat next week about best to address this issue."}, {'account_id': 10267, 'date': '2017-11-06 04:59:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I feel we have very nice code for forcing router processing synchronisation by l3 agent when it receives simultaneous router update(init/update/delete) notifications from server workers.
The root cause for the issues we are seeing are
1) Trying to process router where we shouldn't(not synchronised) i.e fetch_and_sync_all_routers[2]. All the router processing should happen only router processing queue handlers. Even if we going to add any periodic tasks, the task should add router to the queue and only queue handler should process them to force synchronisation.
[2] Infinite retry [3]. Router processing(init/delete/update) is done inside this infinite retry. Though this is helping many times, if the errors are not correctable(because of defective router) this is completely bringing down the agent. When we have a customer deployment with hundreds of routers, finding the root cause for defective router failure is really hard and instead if limit the retry to a count(for example, retry 5 or 10 times) that can avoid bringing down the agent. And this retry really helps cleaning up the router resources(may not be all resources but maximum it can) rather than the approach we are following in these patches.
We need to address these two issues(I see none of the patches  trying to address "infinite retry" issue).
[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/agent/l3/router_processing_queue.pyhttps://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/agent/l3/router_processing_queue.py
[2] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/agent/l3/agent.py#L614
[3] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/agent/l3/agent.py#L529-L542'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-11-06 15:27:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

Anil - yes that is a good assessment.  But do you think there is still a problem where the initialize fails and an update is already in the queue?  It seems like it could, which could lead to the __getitem__ failure we see in the HA code.

I'll add a retry limit to this patch as well, but I'm thinking we need to start combining my three patches into one since there is now more overlap here and we should try and fix this all at once."}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-11-06 15:31:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 10267, 'date': '2017-11-06 15:46:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

> (1 comment)
 > 
 > Anil - yes that is a good assessment.  But do you think there is
 > still a problem where the initialize fails and an update is already
 > in the queue?  It seems like it could, which could lead to the
 > __getitem__ failure we see in the HA code.
Agree Brian. This can happen. 

 > 
 > I'll add a retry limit to this patch as well, but I'm thinking we
 > need to start combining my three patches into one since there is
 > now more overlap here and we should try and fix this all at once.
Thanks Brian. We need single patch with all fixes :)"}, {'account_id': 10267, 'date': '2017-11-06 15:47:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Sorry Brian, my last comment was not properly indented :)
But my reply is there :)'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-11-06 19:04:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-11-06 21:40:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-11-07 16:39:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2017-11-07 17:43:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

(2 comments)

What's the reason why we go with this 3 squashed fixes into one approach? Those seem largely independent fixes for different issues."}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2017-11-07 18:10:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I squashed the changes from the HA code here because they were related to calling into methods when things weren't initialized. commit_message:
Move check_ha_state_for_router() into notification code

As soon as we call router_info.initialize(), we could
possibly try and process a router.  If it is HA, and
we have not fully initialized the HA port or keepalived
manager, we could trigger an exception.

Move the call to check_ha_state_for_router() into the
update notification code so it's done after the router
has been created.  Updated the functional tests for this
since the unit tests are now invalid.

Also added a retry counter to the RouterUpdate object so
the l3-agent code will stop re-enqueuing the same update
in an infinite loop.  We will delete the router if the
limit is reached.

Finally, have the L3 HA code verify that ha_port and
keepalived_manager objects are valid during deletion since
there is no need to do additional work if they are not.

Change-Id: Iae65305cbc04b7af482032ddf06b6f2162a9c862
Closes-bug: #1726370

commit_message:
Add capability to configure simple-crypto backend for barbican

This introduces the ability to configure the simple crypto backend
through a general backends manifest. This manifest will gather all the
backends and enable the relevant configurations depending on whether
they're enabled via t-h-t or not.

Change-Id: I44391b91b01bc03c9773410152e117ec6bbba491

commit_message:
PermitRootLogin for hosts group

Allow login as root user to hosts.
We currently use root user for all our tasks, this causes the integrated
build to fail, and would cause all deploys to fail too, since ansible
can't log into the hosts as the root user.

Change-Id: I8d34cef23b81e5474b8f2c0e7b7d8bbac3a5dc00
(cherry picked from commit 4c92d37c01f59a4c8992863896a8ce0bc2074551)

subject: No longer import nose
messages:
[{'account_id': 9369, 'date': '2017-11-07 01:07:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2017-11-07 01:55:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Why is test-requirements.txt not update to remove nose?'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2017-11-07 02:00:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think I want to re-state my object in a more general terms: is there a point of removing "import nose", but not going all the way and removing all uses of nose? Unless you eradicate it, you cannot claim any packaging advantage, and the coding advantage does not appear to be anything impressive. Observe that not every skip check was possible to replace with a decorator, in this very patch.

So, I think I don't like this unless ./.unittests is fixed to use something else, so we can remove the dependency, and then all the documentation is updated, in CONTRIBUTING.rst, doc/source/development_saio.rst, and such.'}, {'account_id': 9369, 'date': '2017-11-07 03:00:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sure, but that's an eventual goal -- this change was small, distinct and is a step on that path. I didn't want to push some massive patch that does everything, since that's difficult to review."}, {'account_id': 9369, 'date': '2017-11-07 03:07:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2017-11-07 03:10:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Steve, thanks for the patch. Can you share what the long-term goal is? What this is getting us one step closer to?

We've got both testr and nose as test runners now, and I'd prefer that we have only one."}, {'account_id': 9369, 'date': '2017-11-07 04:27:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 9369, 'date': '2017-11-07 04:28:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I think the end goal is to switch to testr everywhere, not just for functional tests, but I suspect the next step is what Pete was talking about, and removing it from test-requirements.txt, perhaps.'}, {'account_id': 9369, 'date': '2017-11-07 04:41:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2017-11-07 17:51:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

Well, if we're focusing on testr... It's used by tox anyway, so might as well."}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2017-11-08 22:01:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2

lgtm'}]

commit_message:
No longer import nose

Since Python 2.7, unittest in the standard library has included mulitple
facilities for skipping tests by decorators as well as an exception.
Switch to that directly, rather than importing nose.

Change-Id: I4009033473ea24f0d0faed3670db844f40051f30

commit_message:
Add missing zuul v3 job definition

The previous patches to add tests to this repo for this
branch left out the actual job definition, resulting in
no tests being run for this repository.

This patch implements the job to ensure that tests are
run as they were before with jenkins.

commit_message:
ESFIX:Fix troveclient error with Chinese character

Now troveclient does not support returning Chinese characters, so
to make changes.This should also avoid other unicode output
problems

Change-Id: Ie948cff4e81806f17c697f50271992cc492c48f4
Closes-Bug: #1720490

- gate-trove-pylint-ubuntu-xenial http://logs.openstack.org/28/485128/1/check/gate-trove-pylint-ubuntu-xenial/bbcde3e/ : SUCCESS in 5m 42s'}, {'account_id': 13562, 'date': '2017-07-31 12:49:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 22608, 'date': '2017-11-01 03:01:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2: Patch Set 1 was rebased.'}, {'account_id': 25113, 'date': '2017-11-01 03:06:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 26311, 'date': '2017-11-01 03:12:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 13562, 'date': '2017-11-02 17:07:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

While I agree that the tasks should have unique numbers and this is a bug, the migration needs to be addressed.

If this code were merged and users upgraded from a previous release, the DB instances they have stored with task states would change stated.  The instances that were in 0x58 'GROWING' now change to state 0x58 'SHRINKING', etc."}, {'account_id': 13562, 'date': '2017-11-03 15:07:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

I gave more thought to the migration path.

As it is right now, the last InstanceTask to be declared with a duplicate ID is the one that is used when the from_code method looks up the InstanceTask.  This is the method used when loading from the DB.

There is not much we can do to try and fix any duplicates in the existing DBs.  To remove the duplication without injecting more DB migration problems we should simply move IDs of the InstanceTasks that are being overwritten and skipped with from_code.  This will retain the current load from DB functionality and will not introduce issues for the other codes as the current patch set does.

I've marked in line which InstanceTasks should have their IDs change and move in the code ordering."}, {'account_id': 22608, 'date': '2017-11-04 05:18:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> (2 comments)
 > 
 > I gave more thought to the migration path.
 > 
 > As it is right now, the last InstanceTask to be declared with a
 > duplicate ID is the one that is used when the from_code method
 > looks up the InstanceTask.  This is the method used when loading
 > from the DB.
 > 
 > There is not much we can do to try and fix any duplicates in the
 > existing DBs.  To remove the duplication without injecting more DB
 > migration problems we should simply move IDs of the InstanceTasks
 > that are being overwritten and skipped with from_code.  This will
 > retain the current load from DB functionality and will not
 > introduce issues for the other codes as the current patch set does.
 > 
 > I've marked in line which InstanceTasks should have their IDs
 > change and move in the code ordering.

hi, Saumel, your comments is helpful. This patch did't consider the minimal impact on code and I will update it. Besides, since the instancetask is grouped by ERROR(start at 0x00) and NONE-ERROR(start at 0x50), I update the UPDATEING task from 0x59 to 0x0c and move it to the behand of 0x0b, but this also break backwards compatibility, I am not sure if it is necessary. Please review."}, {'account_id': 22608, 'date': '2017-11-04 05:24:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 22608, 'date': '2017-11-04 05:51:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

About the impact to a previous release I have some thought.
1. Most time the task_status of an instance is "InstanceTask(0x01, 'NONE', 'No tasks for the instance.')". Other none-error InstanceTask is temporary stored in DB and will change to 0x01 enentually.
2. About  error InstanceTask, according the code show.
https://github.com/openstack/trove/blob/master/trove/instance/models.py#L302
If is_error =True, the output instance status will be error, and all 0x5X nstanceTask has a parameter "is_error=True". 

3. Let's just delete instance which status is error.  :)'}, {'account_id': 13562, 'date': '2017-11-06 15:19:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Thanks.  You did what I asked but unfortunately I put my comments on the wrong items in patch set 1.  The general comment I had was that the second InstanceTask with a given ID should remain with that ID but I incorrectly marked the wrong one for UPDATING in the code review.

I've commented, hopefully correctly, here.

I agree that the convention used in the past was 0x5? were errors, but given the fact the non-error UPDATING InstanceTask was added in that range in the past, it is something we shouldn't change at this point without DB migration.

For code readability I think we should continue to leave the 0x59 UPDATING in numerical order even though it is not an error.  This may help to avoid similar issues happening in the future."}, {'account_id': 22608, 'date': '2017-11-07 02:17:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 13562, 'date': '2017-11-07 18:44:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 22694, 'date': '2017-11-08 03:26:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 25113, 'date': '2017-11-08 03:41:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 26895, 'date': '2017-11-08 20:58:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 26895, 'date': '2017-11-08 20:58:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow+1'}]

commit_message:
Fix duplicate instancetask code.

Each kind of instance task should have a unique code,
BUILDING_ERROR_TIMEOUT_GA and BUILDING_ERROR_REPLICA has the same
code(0x54), UPGRADING_ERROR and UPGRADING = InstanceTask has the same
code(0x59).

Change-Id: I8851ea5cf1a85fb81d010e4d2cca24cea124033f

commit_message:
MongoDB create raise index out of range error

trove/common/strategies/cluster/experimental/mongodb/api.py
In MongoDBCluster.create,  use FOR loop to create config nodes.
But the code"for i in range(1, num_configsvr + 1)" means i start from 1,
while regions[i] in for loop should start from 0, otherwise would cause
the "IndexError: list index out of range" error.

Change-Id: I0e756685a11c6dafd9d44b7f5fe21e9affb10316
Closes-Bug: 1700055

commit_message:
Merge haproxy-octavia-ubuntu into haproxy-octavia

Rather than have a lot of duplicated code, lets just have one
haproxy-octavia element.

Also moving adding of ubuntu backports to happen at 10- rather than 01-.
It is a good pattern to only make elements which begin at 10- or later
so it is easier for potential user added elements to run beforehand.

Change-Id: I396a71040153aa1c92a87d9f609eed25500c8748

[{'created': '2017-10-24 23:17:09.000000000', 'message': "Persist existing LPAR wrapper attributes in DefaultStandardize on resize

The DefaultStandardize object in pypowervm defaults the proc units
factor, max virtio slots, uncapped weight, spp, availability
priority, srr, proc compat, and lpar metric values. nova-powervm
does not pass in these parameters when resizing.

This results in these attributes being set to the default defined
by the DefaultStandardize object for every resize operation. This
change passes those parameters into the DefaultStandardize object.

Note that if the attributes were passed in as part of the flavor
then the flavor's values would be set later in the DefaultStandardize
object by the LPARBuilder.

Closes-Bug: #1722923

commit_message:
Persist existing LPAR wrapper attributes in DefaultStandardize on resize

The DefaultStandardize object in pypowervm defaults the proc units
factor, max virtio slots, uncapped weight, spp, availability
priority, srr, and proc compat (note that the enable lpar metric
parameter isn't included in this stable/pike commit as the minimum
pypowervm requirement for Pike does not support that parameter).
nova-powervm does not pass in these parameters when resizing.

This results in these attributes being set to the default defined
by the DefaultStandardize object for every resize operation. This
change passes those parameters into the DefaultStandardize object.

Note that if the attributes were passed in as part of the flavor
then the flavor's values would be set later in the DefaultStandardize
object by the LPARBuilder.

Closes-Bug: #1722923
Change-Id: I0e9ad0dbbc35658e096636a454ad493492025420
(cherry picked from commit 4bad1ec1654b757c70100fbcc6f51505719d79d9)

commit_message:
Set bind mount propegatation to shared for /var/lib/nova.

This is required for nfs exports mounted by the nova_compute container to be
visible to nova_libvirt.

Depends-on: I8a63c044e15d7ca0f54654e9fc9c5d878461aa25
Change-Id: I55859e744e3c2ebbd6975c96b84b6b0774dc6700
Closes-bug: 1730533

Use rdoproject-based settings for containers and dlrn_hash for images

Jobs deploying with containerized overcloud are running with
docker.io -based settings. This review changes jobs running
on RDO Cloud to use rdoproject images and container settings.

Depends-On: Id8f0e4e2af57e8840d0aeb7eb9b9620e48d05279
Change-Id: I4d15094f9b8d0e4a9463a5f9b4e7a689a1585211

commit_message:
tasks: lxc_cache_create: Use threads when compressing base image

Use multiple threads when compressing the base container image. The
special value of '0' instructs 'xz' to use as many threads as the number
of CPUs on the system. This change improves the total amount of time it
takes to compress the image up to ~85%

Before:
lxc_hosts : Create lxc image ------------------------------------------- 28.42s

After:
lxc_hosts : Create lxc image -------------------------------------------- 3.98s

Change-Id: I5fa162e027882ada4e45a392ae3757f0658cd599
(cherry picked from commit 82f649db95942c4b58b5a53950625bb418dee0a1)

commit_message:
Remove ceilometer-collector from overcloud image

collector has been removed in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/504244/
and package is being deleted in RDO. Although a provides is being added
to keep backwards compatibility, let's remove it from t-p-e

Change-Id: I2d22d088a3adc900eaf995948ba7aaa6aa51ef86

commit_message:
Get DLRN hash before setting up repos and images

When deploying with containerized overcloud and updating
containers prior to deploy, the DLRN hash of the images
used to install should match that of the containers' tags.

This review adds steps to get the DLRN hash and set the
images location, repos baseurl and containers tags.
It also updates the config/release files to
use the path to the DLRN hash related files.

Change-Id: Id8f0e4e2af57e8840d0aeb7eb9b9620e48d05279

commit_message:
Unset MountFlags in docker.service systemd directives

Required to allow bind propegation options to be set on individual bind-mounts.
See https://github.com/moby/moby/issues/19625.

Also https://access.redhat.com/articles/2938171 for rational for using this
option in RHEL/CentOS 7.3.

Change-Id: I8a63c044e15d7ca0f54654e9fc9c5d878461aa25
Related-bug: 1730533

commit_message:
ovn: Remove setting of DockerNeutronApiImage param

tripleo-common sets the DockerNeutronApiImage and DockerNeutronConfigImage
to appropriate neutron ovn image when "openstack image prepare" is called
for OVN deployments.

Closes-bug: #1722543
Change-Id: I26e619488be8bd2ae180969e522879f446753404

commit_message:
tempest: conditional --provider:physical_network

Juniper Contrail associate the use of `--provider:physical_network` to a
SRIOV device. Which means the parameter cannot be used seamlessly.
With this patch, we use the argument only if `public_physical_network` is
not empty.

See: https://www.juniper.net/documentation/en_US/contrail3.1/topics/concept/sriov-with-vrouter-vnc.html

Change-Id: I983cc88f6f31ebb5deabbc8c67a3ec31f48b0f3d

commit_message:
Add support for multiple Cinder RBD backends

Add new CinderRbdExtraPools Heat parameter, which specifies a list of
Ceph pools for use with RBD backends for Cinder. An extra Cinder RBD
backend driver is created for each pool in the list. This is in addition
to the standard RBD backend driver associated with the CinderRbdPoolName.
The new parameter is optional, and defaults to an empty list.

Adding this feature requires changes in two areas:
o The extra Cinder RBD backends get created via a new Puppet parameter
o The Ceph client key that permits access to specific Ceph pools is
  updated to allow client access to the extra RBD pools

Implements: blueprint multiple-cinder-rbd-backend
Depends-On: I3318b9eaef607d6992f9a8cb605817b6f76dd331
Change-Id: If410ed43b2cc70094a3274c1488833fcaae56cca

commit_message:
create subunit test results for the undercloud sanity check

In OpenStack health all the tests are marked as failures
because by default we create a failing subunit result
for all jobs.  We need to create results for the undercloud.

Related-Bug: #1729686
Change-Id: I4850eaadc09035577cb48a367c5f482ed07b7a32

commit_message:
Galera: add support for encrypted SST

When internal TLS is enabled, generate a galera config that enable
encryption of SST rsync traffic.

The configuration relies on a new sst script wsrep_sst_rsync_tunnel,
which encapsulates rsync traffic in a socat-based encrypted tunnel.

Change-Id: I1d6ee8febb596b3ab9dcde3a85a028ee99b2798c
Depends-On: Ia857350ac451fc1bda6659d85019962d3a9d5617
Closes-Bug: #1719885
(cherry picked from commit 9fb617eaea607bc3615edeaf4608fded55045ebd)

commit_message:
Migrates storage-environment.yaml to ceph-ansible

Previously storage-environment.yaml defaulted to deploying Ceph
using puppet-ceph, this change defaults it to ceph-ansible instead.
In addition it adds a new storage-environment-external.yaml file
which should be used when using an external Ceph cluster.

Change-Id: I1dea3b7665dc0da2ab30a89e077ba36cd36b05fd
Closes-Bug: #1724182

commit_message:
Zuul: add file extension to playbook path

Zuul now supports including the file extension on the playbook path
and omitting the extension is now deprecated. Update references
to include the extension.

Conflicts:
    zuul.d/legacy-ironic-inspector-jobs.yaml
    - due to removal of grenade-dsvm job

Change-Id: I95c6dd53713fc1d0a287fce9b42afdce1eba198c
(cherry picked from commit 05230cca8cebe9c1d9a9fc9f8f5cf084ef5d8f57)

commit_message:
Move legacy ironicclient jobs in-tree

This moves the legacy python-ironicclient CI jobs into the
python-ironicclient tree, instead of storing them in
openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs.

This also changes the ironicclient-tempest-dsvm-src job to
inherit from legacy-ironic-dsvm-base instead of legacy-dsvm-base,
since the required projects are the same.

This will give us control as we migrate the legacy jobs to the
new ansible roles.

Change-Id: If0c072e357fbeccc3dee8cc06b96e1bfa42299a7
(cherry picked from commit 9232ebd6d9dda0f6ddec71fe3353abf9a08f31d0)

commit_message:
SUSE: Avoid repositoy refresh and metadata clean up

The only reason we do a refresh is to import the GPG keys and also to
ensure that our metadata is update. However, we don't really need to do
that since zypper is smart to check for outdated metadata. We can also
import the keys when we install packages or updating the distro.

Change-Id: I4f53f33dd31184d2e3c70c6ad93cea857b30895a
(cherry picked from commit 7cc10a7bea9fc0398a7b89cf95f307e9b338df04)

commit_message:
Fixed creation neutron api mapping for security groups

Fixed creation of security group and security group rule via
neutronclient api mapping.
There was a switch from novaclient to neutronclient
for creating a security groups and rules in change
5d5666b10e57a94bcde06c8a296002175d935c7b but
the argument mapping for this function has not been changed.

Change-Id: I1774b73c61adb3b44a61f3f56f99e85f278deb83
Closes-Bug: 1716922
(cherry picked from commit c93f5833e4100d2325994b1bdf8f0d12b70d00c7)

commit_message:
Do not set cluster in maintenance mode during split stack upgrade

This change noops ControllerDeployedServer{Pre,Post}Config to avoid
getting the upgrade of a split stack deployment getting stuck due
to the cluster being in maintenance mode. For reference a similar
change has been done for the regular Controller role in:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/487313/

Change-Id: Idd393011b3c4d0d236780e11a04a59d426750de1
Closes-bug: 1725175

commit_message:
Remove checks for auth_token in JSON-based formatter tests

the auth_token will no longer be returned as-is, as a result of a recent
patch to oslo.context [1]. So this removes these checks from here as
they will break when we get a newer oslo.context.

[1] I2b245c1665c3587be3c476b803122788d186e5d5

Change-Id: Ib3fea55976fb7c469d7b86644cacb802046e561a

commit_message:
Get rid of ensure_* functions from db api

These functions are just aliases to get_* functions and
mostly useless. So it's safe to remove them and use get_*
directly.

Change-Id: Idfa33ca47ddddab384d3817ee17aae6d941f5e44

commit_message:
Add option for Neutron containers to log to stdout/stderr

This adds the option to get the neutron containers to log to stdout.
The option is disabled by default.

bp logging-stdout-rsyslog

commit_message:
Explicitly set healthcheck command.

We were setting them in the Dockerfile's previously.  However this
caused the healtcheck commands to always run regardless of which
process we were running in the container.  This caused 'unhealthy'
containers at times they were never intended to be checked.  This
change makes it so they are explicitly set.

Change-Id: I7bc12d236b3cc7a52d3e6aa706fd04675dad3a9a

commit_message:
Add all services to container scenarios

This commit brings the multinode containers scenario files closer to
their BM variants to add missing services and turning pacemaker on.
These require refactorings in OOOQ in order to support non-containerized
to containerized upgrade jobs across releases. Ceph-ansible is also
going to be switched separately.

Co-Authored-By: Jiri Stransky <jistr@redhat.com>
Depends-On: Ie0e8de54794a9259c0aeb8c67ae0f6a908844093
Change-Id: Icb659509b38575534be27a1881dbe671c40a5436
Related-Bug: #1714905
Related-Bug: #1712070
(cherry picked from commit c504f83c28b986ceb2b92cc0077959158bd11df7)

commit_message:
Add missing IronicInspector service

This is used to select which images to include in the generated files
by passing the heat environment file and role to the 'openstack
overcloud container image prepare' command.

Change-Id: Iefd11f6abdf209b3675aba8cbaa6b0da5619b2f7

commit_message:
Add steps needed when using OVB with a testenv broker

This continues the work to merge the OVB playbook in tripleo-ci with
the OVB playbook here. This should again be a no-op change, with the
only new behavior turned on by setting use_testenv_broker=true.

This change completes the differences between the two playbooks before
the undercloud is installed. There are also slight differences in what
we do after the undercloud is installed in the
baremetal-quickstart-extras playbook. Those will be addressed in the
final patch of this series.

Change-Id: Id24b8c4866f46dcb37a98b682f54101a341f9adb

commit_message:
Fix rights to local_settings.d for dockerized Horizon

For some reasonf that directory doesn't have r/x rights, so when
compress is ran as root, it can access config files in it, but when
horizon is run by apache, it can't, and expects different theme files,
thus failing with OfflineGenerationError. Giving apache access to that
directory fixes the problem and makes the custom theme work.

Closes-bug: #1730911
Change-Id: I53f6db23b036bc9b5a689bbac958550f384194c6

commit_message:
[reno] Prelude for release 2.0

This adds a prelude for the 2.0 major release:

- default API version is 'latest' for both OSC and ironic CLI
- no python-openstackclient requirement
- deprecated 'ironic' CLI

Change-Id: I14d8b286e932cc2b8422100515918612b1a3039c

commit_message:
Revert "Using assertFalse(A) instead of assertEqual(False, A)"

This is not correct,
because assertEqual(False, A) is a stricter check than assertFalse(A).
assertFalse(None) passes, but assertEqual(False, None) will fail.
Therefore, this patch weakened our tests.

Change-Id: I9bbb5d020bda237472f1edc85eab45460d5b5fb2

and omitting the extension is now deprecrated.  Update references

commit_message:
Improve node count indicator in roles step

Instead of only saying how many nodes are available for assignment, we now also
say how many require further action, and how many have already been assigned.
We also indicate how many nodes are in the system altogether.

Change-Id: I061277672a21e382676043245af60882127133f7
(cherry picked from commit 983d3d0b5eea173a1ef5a950e22f71e286039a38)

commit_message:
Healthcheck for nova_migration_target container

nova_migration_target container reuses nova_compute container,
so we have to adapt the health check to support both containers.

Closes-Bug: #1730649
Change-Id: Id48e32b43d2e0cd4319905131f1c0bee9774e5f0

commit_message:
Fix health_manager to exit without waiting

When trying to exit health_manager the terminal
would hang due to a child process using time.sleep().
Now the process uses futurist.periodics to schedule
when to run which allows it to quickly and gracefully
exit.

Also handles the `failover_amphora` not working out or being
cancelled correctly and logging the statistics of those occurences
instead of incorrectly assuming everything always works out.

Co-Authored-By: Adam Harwell <flux.adam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Joshua Harlow <jxharlow@godaddy.com>

Change-Id: I870edaab73ab20a9322c8bc1bd2514897417d12a

commit_message:
Addition of Nuage as mechanism driver for ML2

Adding composable services for Nuage mechanism driver for ML2. This
is separate from Nuage as the core plugin and intentional duplication
of Nuage under puppet services. Parameters required for working of
Nuage as mechanism driver are also added.

Change-Id: I2b564610721152c4f4dab9da79442256ba8d0b33

commit_message:
Zuul: add file extension to playbook path

Zuul now supports including the file extension on the playbook path
and omitting the extension is now deprecrated.  Update references
to include the extension.

Change-Id: I3141f12d0de00c3d8def2862881326f349edd479
(cherry picked from commit 644f2c326fa2a584dfe391bfccf78e36f2e63408)

commit_message:
[networking-odl] Fix grafana dashboards

As part of the Zuul migration the grafana dashboards broke because of
the way the statistics need to accessed, as well as a difference in
naming of the jobs. This patch addresses both issues and also brings
up-to-date the graphs with the jobs defined in the Zuul definitions.

Depends-On: I1270bcb260ea324b51eb6e6e9e9fef2a61ef5e27
Change-Id: Ia4fa570647751014df97c418ed985850a0d8f946

commit_message:
Add zuul3 jobs in-tree

copied all over from general config repos,
renamed to better match how ironic now names jobs.

Conflicts:
    The grenade-dsvm job was removed. Since stable/newton has
    been EOL'd and doesn't exist, the job tries to upgrade from
    master instead of newton, and it fails.

Change-Id: If8195b909dba152e978aac33241424ecfd0777dd
(cherry picked from commit 843ca2258b86d81f1d2dd6362b6589fa0446aa09)

for naming, see https://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/drivers.html#v3-naming'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2017-11-07 16:22:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

@Andreas, that link is useful but a bit too late. I think we should have someone go through all the ironic projects/jobs and make the names consistent. I'll make a note to do this. (I'll be really happy to get rid of the 'dsvm' part!)

We might want to keep the 'pxe_ipmitool' part in the name, since it is useful to know which driver is being tested.

So for now, to be somewhat consistent with existing job names, maybe 'virtualbmc-tempest-dsvm-pxe_ipmitool-src'."}, {'account_id': 11297, 'date': '2017-11-08 03:35:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 11297, 'date': '2017-11-08 03:38:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Replace the deprecated nova_metadata_ip

As [1], the option nova_metadata_ip has been deprecated and
we can use nova_metadata_host instead. This patch makes devstack
do it.

[1]: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/neutron/tree/neutron/conf/agent/metadata/config.py#n49

Change-Id: Ifda43ec8c7743af6acdd3003c55c081ef5b1311c
